Families, your student could receive a free Chromebook! Youthprise and MN Afterschool Advance are offering Chromebooks for no additional cost to families to help with distance learning this fall. And thanks to scholarship dollars from Youthprise, we’ve been able to expand the eligibility rules for families to qualify! Now, families can receive a Chromebook if:
They have a student in grades K-12; and
They qualify for Free or Reduced Price Lunch or had a parent/guardian lose a job in 2020

Learn more at http://www.mnafterschool.org/chromebooks
**Students at ISD 318 will still receive iPads for distance learning through the school.

post_text:
Last week, Governor Tim Walz provided school districts with local control for opening schools based on the number of COVID-19 cases in our community. His office has created a matrix that is based on the average cases in our community over a two-week period.

Initial projections show that we are scheduled to reopen for face-to-face instruction. This could change if cases increase in our area. We will be working with Itasca County Public Health in the coming days to verify our cases and find where we fall in the matrix. Our goal is to get as many children back to our schools as possible.

We know that there will be families who don’t feel comfortable sending their children back to school at this point. We will offer robust remote instruction to those families. Registration for 318 ConnectEd will be available soon.

Join Superintendent Matt Grose tomorrow at 3:00 pm for another Facebook Q&A as we discuss what the Governor’s announcement means for our district.

post_text:
Parents and families, as we plan for fall reopening, we need to hear from you! We don’t yet know which scenario the Governor will implement (that announcement is coming Thursday), but to help us plan for transportation needs, technology needs and more, we are asking you to complete a quick questionnaire. We need to hear from all parents and guardians by Sunday, August 2. https://www.surveymonkey.com/r/318FallPlanning.

Our fall reopening plan will be complete and shared with the public on Monday, August 10. At that time we will return to our families, staff, and community members for additional feedback. Thank you for your support as we plan our return to learn.

text:
Parents and families, as we plan for fall reopening, we need to hear from you! We don’t yet know which scenario the Governor will implement (that announcement is coming Thursday), but to help us plan for transportation needs, technology needs and more, we are asking you to complete a quick questionnaire. We need to hear from all parents and guardians by Sunday, August 2. https://www.surveymonkey.com/r/318FallPlanning.

Our fall reopening plan will be complete and shared with the public on Monday, August 10. At that time we will return to our families, staff, and community members for additional feedback. Thank you for your support as we plan our return to learn.

SURVEYMONKEY.COM
ISD 318 Fall Reopening

post_text: This week is Severe Weather Awareness week. It pays to be prepared!
shared_text:
DPS.MN.GOV
Weather Safety - Storms, Hail and Lightning

Itasca County Sheriff's Office
April 14 at 5:00 AM ·

Storms, Hail and Lightning

Thunderstorms affect relatively small areas, compared with most other storms. The typical thunderstorm is 15 miles in diameter and lasts for 30 minutes — but whatever their size, all thunderstorms are dangerous.

Severe thunderstorms produce large hail or winds of at least 58 mph. Some wind gusts can exceed 100 mph and produce tornado-like damage. That’s why many communities will sound their outdoor sirens for damaging straight-line winds.

https://dps.mn.gov/divisions/hsem/weather-awareness-preparedness/Pages/severe-weather-lightning-hail-storms.aspx

post_text:
Check out this GRHS #DistanceLearningWin! https://youtu.be/v7ylv1w2i6M
It's a team effort for our Greenhouse and Landscaping students! So many people came together to help Ag teacher Rachel Newman create a Spring Project Package. North In Bloom Floral added corsage kits and donated terrarium plants, Second Harvest North Central Food Bank provided nine different seeds for planting, a University of Minnesota Extension grant provided microgreen pea seeds, high school paraprofessionals helped package it all, custodians helped with bags and transportation, and Food and Nutrition department donated banana boxes to keep it all together. We love the creativity and community support!

post_text:
As you may be aware, this morning, Governor Walz directed all K-12 public and charter schools to close by Wednesday, March 18th for a two week period. All ISD 318 schools will close at the end of the school day on Tuesday, March 17 and reopen on Monday, March 30. This closure includes all after-school and extra curricular activities.

We will continue to provide the latest updates via our Blackboard Instant Alert System. If you did not receive a phone call or email from our system this morning, please contact your building secretary to ensure your contact information is current.

At this point, the plan from the state is that schooling will resume on March 30th, perhaps in the form of distance learning. It would be wise for parents and guardians to begin thinking about what would happen if our closure were to be extended longer and learning continues through a distance option.

We will also continue to post the latest updates on our website at https://www.isd318.org/page/3525.

As you may be aware, this morning, Governor Walz directed all K-12 public and charter schools to close by Wednesday, March 18th for a two week period. All ISD 318 schools will close at the end of the school day on Tuesday, March 17 and reopen on Monday, March 30. This closure includes all after-school and extra curricular activities.

We will continue to provide the latest updates via our Blackboard Instant Alert System. If you did not receive a phone call or email from our system this morning, please contact your building secretary to ensure your contact information is current.

At this point, the plan from the state is that schooling will resume on March 30th, perhaps in the form of distance learning. It would be wise for parents and guardians to begin thinking about what would happen if our closure were to be extended longer and learning continues through a distance option.

We will also continue to post the latest updates on our website at https://www.isd318.org/page/3525.

post_text: We want families, staff, and students to know that we are actively monitoring the changing situation with the coronavirus disease known as COVID-19. We are working closely with the Minnesota Department of Health (MDH), the Minnesota Department of Education (MDE), and local public health officials as they respond to developments in the spread of the virus. You will find our latest updates on our website at https://www.isd318.org/page/3525. This link is displayed on our homepage and on the nursing page under the Services tab. We want to reassure you that we are not taking these precautions out of fear, but are doing so to minimize the spread of any illness, including influenza.

post_text:
Thank you to everyone who supported the Itasca County Knock Out Hunger event!

The group packed and distributed about 52,000 meals at the event attended by about 150 people. They raised $15,000 and received a 20,000 meal match to take them past our 60,000 meal goal! When all is over with the group will have generated about 72,000 meals. That's enough food to feed Itasca County's food insecure for about 8 months!

https://youtu.be/Qs_j68HPvQo

post_text:
Thank you to everyone who made a suggestion for naming the new Grand Rapids Elementary Schools. The naming committee reviewed and then worked together to create a list of five pairs of recommendations. We appreciate all of the suggestions honoring individuals, however, the committee felt it difficult to choose just two people out of all the great suggestions. Instead, the names focus on nature or landmark features that can also be represented in Ojibwe.

Tell us your favorite at https://www.surveymonkey.com/r/318ElemNameFinalist. Your votes will help us finalize the recommendations that will be presented to the School Board on February 10.

post_text:
Due to weather and road conditions, all schools in ISD 318 will start two hours late on today, December 9. This includes schools in both Bigfork and in Grand Rapids. Buses will run their regular routes and students should be at their stop two hours later than their usual pick-up time.

The final decision to keep your child home lies with you. Should you choose to keep your child home, we will always support that decision. We know that the safety of your children is foremost in your mind, as it is in ours, and simply ask that you report your child’s absence to the school.
